<#/> The more you know about these principles and precepts and the more effectively you manage your business, the greater will be your success. <#/>In your goals to improve your business, earn good profits, and reach greater heights,
 nothing will help you more than your ability to manage your business well. <#/>After going through this book you will acquire the necessary background. <#/>But it will not be until you start practising what you have learnt that you will begin to manage y
our business efficiently.}{\v0\f0 </X>
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f56\fs20 {\f0 <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 Your great role }{\f0\fs24 </h>}{\b\f0\fs24 
\par <#/>}{\f0\fs24  Your business is important to everybody in the country. <#/>In the first place it helps create employment even if that is only one job. <#/>This country needs as many employment opportunities as ca
n be found. <#/>In running a small business you are reducing the unemployment problem in the country. <#/>Your business is important to the economy than you may be thinking. <#/>All small businesses in this country together produce goods and services that
 
meet the needs of millions of consumers. <#/>You also help increase production and generate income. <#/>Finally and most important you help your families meet their basic needs - food, shelter, clothing etc. <#/>So you play a great role in nation building
.
\par <#/> Go through the book carefully, understand the subject matter well, put what you have learnt into practice and become a successful small business manager. <#/>It will be your step towards becoming a business magnate.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 2. BUSINESS OPPORTUNITIES <}{\f0\fs24 /h>
\par <#/> Business management begins when you have started a business. <#/>Identification of business opportunities is the foundation for starting a business. <#/>Your ability to manufacture a product, or offer a service becomes the source of further busin
ess opportunities. <#/>Correct identification of business opportunities is one of the most important ingredients of business success. <#/>So give it very serious consideration.
\par <#/> To begin with, you have to identify your own skills and business desires. 
<#/>Skills refer to your area of education and training background. <#/>The products you want to offer may be related to these areas. <#/>If you have had any kind of training it is advisable to locate business opportunities related to that particular trai
n
ing since you have developed the expertise in an area of your choice. <#/>What others, like you, are doing also helps to identify business opportunities. <#/>For example, if a friend of yours is a tailor and makes a reasonable profit or, your own sister i
s a successful hairdresser, you may follow suit.
\par <#/> When trying to emulate what others are doing you must be realistic; you must try to match your education and training background to find out if you have the right skills for making the intended business 
a success. <#/>For example, if your expertise is in motor vehicle repair you may not do well as a <-/hotelier>. <#/>Wrong assessment can lead to failure.
\par <#/> A common question asked by those who have had no special training is what business opportunities 
are available for them? The answer to this question is that business opportunities are many and varied. <#/>One can take up retailing like running a grocery kiosk, selling newspapers, house to house selling, running a poultry farm; selling curious, second
 hand dresses, books, or for that matter even selling eggs. <#/>And if you have the necessary capital and/or expertise, manufacturing.
\par <#/> Another important thing to consider is how relevant and desirable to you the area of your choice is. <#/>If you are v
ery much interested in the business you will definitely be highly motivated to do your best. <#/>So before you invest your money and spend a lot of energy on a business enterprise, think seriously whether you like the particular area.
\par <#/> The market situa
tion will also help you to identify business opportunities. <#/>It could be in the village or town where you were born, or in another part of the country. <#/>Studying the local or national market can help you identify good business opportunities. <#/>If 
y
ou are not clear in this exercise you can get help from your friends, relatives or from a specialist consultant. <#/>Finding out what products or services have a ready market can be a great help in identifying business opportunities. <#/>K-MAP can provide
 some useful guidance to this end.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 3. MARKET STUDY }{\f0\fs24 </h>
\par <#/> Once you have identified business opportunities you must engage in market study. <#/>This is to analyse the market to find out details about the product or services you want to make or pro
vide. <#/>Details include things like the type of product or service that will have a good demand, product or service mix, and who your potential customers are? Where they are. <#/>What is the quantity you can sell? What will be the acceptable, reasonable
, profitable and appealing prices? How the product or service should be moved to the final consumer, when and where the selling outlets would be made available.
\par <#/> The information you gather from the answers to the above questions will help you decide several things, such as:-
\par <#/>- Whether it is worthwhile to engage in the business line you have identified.
\par <#/>- What materials, tools and equipment - and in what quantities - are required to run the business.
\par <#/>- How much money will be required to start and run the business.
\par <#/>- The sales volume that you will be able to realise.
\par <#/>- The cash flow for a given period of time.
\par <#/>- Profit for a particular period of time.
\par <#/>- The location of the market.
\par <#/>- The strength of the market.
\par <#/>- The best and most effective ways of reaching the market.
\par <#/>- The most satisfying and profitable way of distributing the products/services.
\par <#/>- The right price to charge.
\par <#/>- The right product or service mix.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 Marketing }{\f0\fs24 </h>
\par <#/> Before you go into business you should establish whether there is a market for what you want to sell and the nature and extent of that market.
\par <#/> It pays to remember what a market is. <#/>A market is people. <#/>A market comprises of people with income which they are willing to spend on the type of product you intend to produce.
\par <#/> The information you get from the market study (also called market survey or market research) must be used in marketing your product. <#/>It is in your interest to satisf
y market requirements in the business line you have identified, for that is the best way to earn reasonable profit. <#/>This involves the production of the right product, offering of the right service, providing the product or service at the right place a
t the right time, in the right product (service) mix, and finally selling at the right price.
\par <#/> Marketing should also involve adopting the right approach to attract customers, and keep them. <#/>Marketing is very essential if you want to become a successful businessman. <#/>This is more so if you are faced with competition.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 4. PLANNING }{\f0\fs24 </h>
\par <#/> Planning is a very important management function. <#/>And to become successful it is very important to remember that you are the one responsible for plann
ing your business. <#/>Whether you are going to start a new enterprise or whether you will continue operating the current business, or expand it, is something that has to be properly planned.
\par <#/> True, you may be able to get advice from others, but it is you to make your business a success. <#/>Thus you have to be seriously involved in its planning.
\par <#/> Planning is how you want to realise what you want to achieve. <#/>If you want to start business you should know things like what quantity you can produce 
or buy for sale within a given period of time, how much it will cost to produce or buy etc. <#/>If you wish to set up a business, decide the type of enterprises and do the following.
\par <#/>- Write down the different items you require.
\par <#/>- Find out the cost and prepare an estimate. <#/>You can call this an expenditure budget. <#/>This is very important and directly affects your preparation of an accurate budget.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 The benefits of a good plan/budget }{\f0\fs24 </h>
\par <#/> An accurate budget will help you in many ways:
\par <#/>- It will give you a correct picture of the amount of money you will require to spend in order to start and run the business, or it will show you how much money will be needed to operate the business over a given period of time, like a month.
\par <#/>- It will help you to look for ways and means of raising money or credit.
\par <#/>- It will help you to organise ways and means of cutting losses.
\par <#/>- It will help you to calculate profits over a period of time.
\par }{\b\v\f0\fs24 <&/>table
\par }{\b\f0\fs24 <#/>}{\f0\fs24  It is necessary to prepare an expenditure budget for any kind of business - manufacturing, service or farming.
\par <#/>- Find out how much it will cost to produce one unit or provide one service. <#/>This can be done with the help of a production budget or service operation budget.
\par <#/>- Estimate how many units you can produce within a given period of time under normal circumstances.
\par <#/>- Deliver the products in the most effective way you can.
\par <#/>If you are already in business, do the following:
\par <#/>- Think out what you want your business to bring next year, e.g. Sales Shs. 50,000/-.
\par <#/>- Think and write down the ways you can get this sales volume.
\par <#/>- Think of the cost of getting the sales target.
\par <#/>- Calculate the profit you can earn.
\par <#/>When thinking of the above points, concentrate on the following areas of your business:
\par 1. Sales
\par 2. The direct costs
\par 3. The indirect costs
\par <#/> It is necessary to estimate these three areas as accurately as possible so that you have a clear idea of the profit you are going to earn. <#/>When you have run your business for sometime it is possible to make realistic estimates of future sales.

\par <#/>When you know the three areas well it becomes helpful to:
\par - Estimate the profit you will make
\par - Plan to reduce costs
\par - Plan to raise money when necessary
\par - Plan to do whatever may be necessary to realise the sales target.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 5. COSTING <}{\f0\fs24 /h>
\par <#/> Cost
ing is the method you use to calculate how much each product or service costs to produce (or provide) and sell. <#/>It is very necessary for you to know your costs as accurately as possible. <#/>Otherwise you could be selling below cost without knowing; a
nd this would mean making losses, or even ruin of your business.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24 Benefits of Costing <}{\f0\fs24 /h>
\par <#/>- Helps to set prices
\par <#/>- Helps to find out which inputs are most or least expensive
\par }\pard\plain \s138\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \v\f56\lang2057 {\v0\f0 <#/>- Helps in assessing how well any new strategy to improve your business is working.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f56\fs20 {\f0 <#/>}{\f0\fs24 - Helps to adjust profit margins. <#/>This is very important when you are faced with competition.
\par <#/> Before you think of costing one product or one service job, you must calculate the total costs. <#/>In order to do this you must 
keep a record of all the costs. <#/>Book-keeping can help you here. <#/>To know the total costs you must know the different types of costs. <#/>In your business there are two types of costs.
\par <#/>(i) }{\b\f0\fs24 Direct costs:}{\f0\fs24  material cost + labour costs
\par <#/>(ii) }{\b\f0\fs24 Indirect costs:}{\f0\fs24  costs you incur on all the other items in running your business such as building, machines and tools and their maintenance, replacements and repair
\par <#/>Included in indirect costs are also
\par - salaries paid to you and others not directly involved in production
\par - office costs such as telephone, postage and stationery.
\par - Selling costs other than salaries, interests charges and licences etc. <#/>also fall into the indirect costs bracket.
\par <X_>}{\v\f0\fs24 <#/> Note that the more units you produce from the same premises,
 the lower will be the indirect costs per unit of production. <#/>Thus increasing output tends to bring down the total costs per unit of production. <#/>This is called economies of scale. <#/>By lowering your unit costs through the economies of scale you 
can charge lower prices, thus selling more and increasing your total profit.
\par <#/> Accurate and continuous costing is a necessary tool for efficient business management. }{\f0\fs24 </X></I>
